lack of limb salvage despite patent bypass (n = 23, 34%), intraoperative bypass 
failure (n = 6, 9%), and exposed/infected bypass (n = 5, 8%). The 23 patients 
with patent grafts required amputations because of hindfoot necrosis (n = 6), 
persistent forefoot necrosis (n = 6), acute diabetic foot infection (n = 6), and 
various other reasons (n = 5). Using life-table analysis, survival for the whole 
group was 56% at 12 months and 17% at 48 months. Patients with limb loss despite 
a patent bypass fared the worst with survival of 21% at 2 years.
CONCLUSIONS: Bypass thrombosis caused half of the amputations after limb salvage 
surgery. A patent bypass was functioning at the time of amputation in another 
third. Survival after failure of limb salvage was abysmal, especially in 
patients with patent bypasses.

