[Should asymptomatic carotid artery stenoses be operated?].

[Article in French]

Mas JL(1).

Author information:
(1)Service de Neurologie, Centre Raymond Garcin, Hôpital Sainte-Anne, Paris.

Compared to asymptomatic stenoses, asymptomatic carotid artery stenoses are 
associated with a relatively low risk of ipsilateral cerebral infarction: 
approximately 2% per year for stenoses reducing the diameter of the arterial 
lumen by 60% or more. The benefit of surgery is therefore limited. In the ACAS 
study, the risk of ipsilateral cerebral infarction was reduced by 50% by 
surgery, which corresponds to an absolute reduction of the risk of only 1% per 
year. Carotid endarterectomy should therefore be reserved for patients presumed 
to be at greater risk of cerebral infarction (stenosis greater than 80%, 
haemodynamic repercussions), provided that the patient's age and life expectancy 
are compatible with long-term prevention and that this treatment can be 
conducted at a low risk. In every case, the patient must be precisely informed 
about the expected benefits and risks of this operation.

