The effects of dementia in German acute care hospitals.

Dinkel RH(1), Lebok UH.

Author information:
(1)Institute of Quantitative Demography, Otto Friedrich University of Bamberg, 
Germany.

In this study a representative sample of German acute care hospitals is used to 
describe the effects of dementia within acute care hospitals. Data from hospital 
patients above age 60 with the diagnosis dementia (ICD 290, 293, 294 and 310), 
collected over an observation period of 12 years, are compared with nondemented 
hospital patients at the same ages. The differences in the average length of 
stay between demented and nondemented patients are only relatively small in 
German acute care hospitals. The degree of multimorbidity is higher and hospital 
infections are more frequent for demented patients. The main differences occur 
with mortality: demented inpatients of both sexes experience a hospital 
mortality which is about twice as high as for nondemented patients at the same 
ages.

